<HEAD>



<TITLE>Court TV Trial Report</TITLE>



</HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#BB0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">



<IMG SRC="/report/trheader.gif" ALT="Trial Report" WIDTH="600" HEIGHT="90" BORDER="0">



<H3>The Key Testimony</H3>

<b>August 21</b><br>
The state start presenting evidence in the trial of a Atlanta businessman accused of killing his wife and her friend.<p>

During opening statements, <b>prosecutor Penny Penn </b>laid out the state's case but did not offer a motive for the double killings. The state does not, of course,  have to show a motive. However, the law does say that once the defense introduces evidence of justification, the state must prove beyond a reasonable doubt that the killings were not justified.<p>

Penn simply stated that the evidence will show that Lewis Joyner killed Ruby Joyner and Halima Jones, and that it was not done in self-defense. The state's case appears to rely heavily on the fact that Joyner fled to New York City -- for the seemingly suspicious reason of obtaining a new driver's license -- after the deaths. <p>

Penn contrasted Joyner's actions while the women were missing to the actions of Jones' ex-boyfriend John Dunbar. He immediately contacted the police when he was found out the women were missing, and anxiously urged Joyner to do the same. She concluded her statement by saying that any alleged relationship between Joyner and Lewis was irrelevant in this case.<p>

In stark contrast to Penn, <b>defense attorney Steven Sadow's</b> opening was a high-energy emotional tour of the defense version of events that took place on the evening of November 15, 1995. In what he said was an impulsive move, Sadow began his presentation by introducing the defendant to the jury. He walked Joyner over to the jury box and asked the jurors to take a look at the man they would be judging, to see him as a human being, and to keep an open mind throughout the prosecution's case.<p>

Sadow said Joyner and Jones had  been having a secret affair for months. Ruby Joyner and Dunbar suspected as much, he said.<p>

Then he described the defense version of the events leading to the death of the two women: Joyner met the women the night on November 15 in the parking lot of a bar and restaurant near the
Hartsfield International Airport. Ruby Joyner went into the bar. While she was away, Joyner and Jones embraced and got out some cocaine. Ruby Joyner appeared at the driver's door and offered to drive while her husband and Jones were in the back seat of the van doing cocaine.<p>

At some point, Ruby Joyner stopped the van and got out. Sadow said she took a pistol from her purse and yelled, "you cheating bitch. I caught you with my husband." She then shot Jones through the window.<p>

She then turned the gun on Joyner, who fled into the woods. She followed him, and a violent struggle followed. Ruby Joyner eventually got one of Joyner's fingers in her mouth and would not let go. As he tried to get his finger out of her mouth, she got hit in the head, and she died. He then said that police knew of this version of events early on but did not conduct tests to verify the story.<p>

Sadow also told the jury that they would hear testimony about Ruby Joyner's violent and jealous nature. And he said that the reason she obtained a gun was because she wanted to protect herself after getting mugged in her hotel while on a vacation to Ft. Lauderdale in September of 1995.<p>

<b>Kamilah Torres-Carmona</b>, a co-worker of Ruby Joyner, testified about Ruby Joyner's feelings towards guns. She testified that Joyner had told her that she was terrified of guns. But on cross-examination, she said that the conversation in which Joyner allegedly expressed her fear took place months before the Joyners' trip to Ft. Lauderdale. On redirect-examination, Torres-Carmona described how Joyner looked after she returned from the trip: her eyes were seriously injured, as if she had been beaten. She said Joyner told her she had been mugged. But the witness said she didn't believe Joyner's story.<p>

<b>John Dunbar</b> told the jury about how the Joyners met him and Jones, and how they became friends. His most important testimony concerned the events after the women disappeared. Dunbar said he had  numerous conversations with Joyner and he repeatedly urged him to go to police to file a missing persons report on his wife.<p>

On cross-examination, Dunbar said that he had indeed suspected Jones was having an affair with Joyner. By referring to phone bills, he identified numerous calls made from the Joyners' home to Jones' cell phone, and vice versa, at times when Ruby Joyner was at work. He also testified that he had seen Joyner and Jones use cocaine together.<p>

<b>Lester Page</b>, a friend of the defendant and the victims, testified that Joyner had told him he had checked into a Days Inn in Atlanta on November 16 before flying to New York to get a new driver's license and to be near his family. Page also said that he had urged Joyner to return to Atlanta, and to get in touch with his wife's family.<p>

On cross-examination, Page testified that Joyner had long been paranoid about driving around without a license. He also said Joyner was not a violent person. He identified a copy of the new license that Joyner in fact obtained in New York City on November 17th.<p>

Ruby Joyner's former boss <b>Mary Dukes </b> told the court what Ruby wore to work on the day she died, which included a brown sweater like the one found at the crime scene on Camp Creek Parkway. She also testified that Joyner called on November 16 to say that his wife would not be at work that day and had not come home the night before.<p>

In the most emotional testimony of the day, Ruby Joyner's niece <b>Coretta Thomas </b>broke down in tears as she described her aunt as a kind, supportive, trustworthy person. She also said that although she had made the hotel arrangements for the vacation in Ft. Lauderdale, her aunt never mentioned getting mugged. But her most important testimony was that Joyner had told her not to tell other family members that his wife was missing, saying he didn't want to alarm them. <p>

On cross-examination, Thomas admitted that she had also felt that Lewis Joyner was a kind and supportive person.<p>

<b>Velma Livingston</b>, another niece of Ruby Joyner, also testified about the injuries to her aunt's eyes after the Florida trip. She said her aunt explained it as a bad eye infection. Livingston also testified that when her family urged Lewis Joyner to return to Atlanta in case his wife tried to contact him, he said he never planned to go back, and talked about getting a passport.<p>

On cross-examination, Livingston was asked when she first told anyone about Joyner's passport comments. She did not give a clear answer. She also was asked about her aunt's drinking habits. Livingstone said she was a social drinker who never had more than a glass of wine at a time.<p>

<b>Peachtree City Police Detective William Weston</b> told
the whole story from start to finish about what happened in this case, starting from his first contacts with Lewis Joyner on November 16. Joyner maintained contact with Weston while police searched for the missing women. One of the more compelling areas of testimony was when Weston said that Joyner had told him he had lost his wallet while he was looking for the women. When Weston asked whether Joyner had canceled his credit cards Joyner said he had not.<p>

On cross examination, Sadow questioned Weston about records of conversations and other documents relevant to this case that Weston did not turn over to the prosecution or defense. After the judge told Weston he had to get these items for Sadow, the defense attorney reserved the right to call Weston back to the stand later.<p>

Weston also admitted that he lied to Joyner when he was trying to get him to return to Atlanta, telling him he was not a suspect in the killings. He also admitted that he did this even though Joyner had honestly told him about where he was, what flight he had taken and planned to return on, about his hotel, about the location of his GMC Jimmy at the airport in Atlanta, and about his getting a driver's license in New York.<p>

<b>Georgia Bureau of Investigation Agent Samuel Baity</b>gave the basic run-down of what happened when and where during the investigation for the missing women. He also testified about locating the crime scene off of Camp Creek Parkway. He said several items were found that led police to conclude that the crime had occurred at that location. The items included a sweater like Ruby Joyner's, bullet casings, and a shoe that belonged to Ruby Joyner. Baity was one of two Atlanta-area police who made the trip to New York City to find Lewis Joyner.<p>

On cross examination, Sadow questioned Baity about a series of technical errors made by police and the prosecution team (i.e. a reversed image print in of photo of Joyner's back, and the fact that the videotape from the Days Inn skipped over the time of day that Joyner allegedly checked in). He also responded to questions about examining the crime scenes at night, rather than in daylight, saying that the techniques work just as well at night, and that, in fact, some investigation was done in daylight.<p>

<b>Dekalb County Medical Examiner Paul Kelhofer </b>described the investigation done at the scene where the bodies were found. Defense attorney Sadow questioned Kelhofer about whether Georgia Bureau of Investigation crime scene special agent Sam House was following proper procedure. Kelhofer admitted that when he arrived, House was not wearing the entire uniform that police procedure required.<p>

<b>Atlanta homicide detective Rick Chambers </b> testified about the police meetings with Jeff Lester. Lester eventually called police and asked them to make a deal. That is when he told police what Joyner had told him in Newark, New Jersey. On cross-examination, Sadow asked Chambers why hair was taken from Lester for examination. He said that it had been taken because the piece of hair found on the women initially appeared to be Caucasian.<p>


<b>August 22</b><br>

<B>FBI Agent Peter McFarland </b>, the crime scene specialist who photographed and investigated the Camp Creek Parkway location,  identified the photos and items seized in the early morning hours of November 25. Some of the items included an overcoat, a sweater, Joyner's prescription sunglasses, broken women's glasses belonging to Ruby Joyner,  a rose-colored washcloth with stains on it, shell casings (three were found in the street and two were in the woods where clothing items were located), and one unfired bullet.<p>

On cross-examination, defense attorney Sadow questioned McFarland on why the bullet casings that were found in the woods were not tested at the GBI crime lab, but the casings found on the street were tested. McFarland said the casings found in the woods appeared older than those found on the street, but that he was not the person who made the decision not to test them. In general, Sadow has attempted to portray the entire police investigation of this case as sloppy. Throughout his questioning, Sadow seemed to be trying to show that police did not do enough to verify Joyner's story.<p>


<b>Brian Kaiser</b>, a licensed optician, verified that the prescription sunglasses found at the Camp Creek Parkway crime scene belonged to Lewis Joyner's. Kaiser also verified that the pieces of broken eyeglasses probably belonged to Ruby Joyner. Sadow's cross was brief and mainly just reiterated the fact that Ruby Joyner's vision would be somewhat fuzzy without her glasses, and that the defendant had very poor eyesight, both for distances and close up.<p>

The most compelling testimony of the day came from pathologist <b>Dr. Gerald Gowitt</b>.

According to Dr. Gowitt, Halima Jones died of a single gunshot wound to the head. The bullet entered her head on the right side, below her ear, and exited on the left side, above her ear. He also said it would be impossible to tell the physical positioning of either Jones or her assailant when Jones was shot. <p>

He also testified that:<P>


@ It was impossible to tell exactly the caliber of the weapon used, although a .380 semi-automatic--which would be consistent with the bullet casings found on the scene--could have produced the wound. <p>

@ The shot to the head would have produced substantial blood loss. <p>

@ The other abrasions on Jones' body could have been caused by her falling  after being shot, or by moving around in the van as it was driven from Camp Creek Parkway to the airport.<p>

Dr. Gowitt testified that the autopsy of Ruby Joyner took considerably longer than that of Jones, because of the complicated nature and large number of wounds. In his opinion, the cause of death was a combination of blunt trauma to the head and some strangulation.<p>

He also made the following points:

@ Ruby Joyner's body was covered with twigs and other foliage when it was brought to his lab.

@ Her shirt, lace undershirt and bra were all raised over her breasts when she was found, and she had large abrasions on her back, and upper body.

@ She had cuts and lacerations all over her hands. Dr. Gowitt said some of the wounds were probably defensive. He said she probably had her hands on her head at some point, as if to ward off blows to her head.<p>

@ She has numerous severe wounds around the head and face although Dr. Gowitt could not say how many times she had been struck.<P>

@ Ruby Joyner was probably rendered unconscious or at least incapacitated at some point from the blows to her head.<p>

@ Her wounds were consistent with being beaten with a handgun. <p>

On cross examination, Dr. Gowitt testified that blood spatter evidence would not necessarily be visible in the van, even if Jones was shot inside the van. If Jones was shot outside the van, blood probably would have gotten on the exterior of the van when her body was dragged into the vehicle. <p>

He also said the direction of the bullet's path through Jones' head could be consistent with her being shot while she sat in the back of the van by a person shooting through the driver's side door.<p>

He also made the following points:<p>

@ Jones had a large amount of cocaine in her system, and probably died within an hour or two of taking the cocaine. <p>

Jones' shoes were almost immaculately clean, indicating she had not walked into the wooded crime scene.<p>

@ Ruby Joyner had a large amount of alcohol in her system, although that may have been the result of decomposition, not consumption of alcoholic beverages. <p>

@ She as probably having her period when she died. (Defense attorney Sadow suggested in his opening statement that this may have contributed to her aggression.) <p>

@ The wounds around her mouth could be consistent with her having someone's (Joyner's) finger in her mouth. The injuries to her hands also could  be consistent with aggressive wounds.<p>

<b>Patrick Angell</b>, a friend and former employee of defendant, was called to testify to establish the fact that Joyner had a habit of always carrying a rag with him to wipe away perspiration. This is relevant because a rose-colored rag with reddish-brown (blood-colored) stains on it was located at the Camp Creek crime scene.<p>

<b>Jeff Lester</b>testified about meeting with Joyner in Newark after the defendant fled to New York. Lester claims Joyner told him that Jones and Ruby Joyner -- who had been using cocaine -- called Joyner and asked him to go for a drive with them near the airport. Ruby Joyner found out about here husband's affair with Jones and she shot Jones in the van. Joyner jumped out of the parked van, and thought his wife was going to shoot him. They fought over the gun and he shot her. <p>

Lester also said Joyner asked him to go to the crime scene because he had left his hat and beeper and his wife's jacket in the area, along the Camp Creek Parkway. Joyner also allegedly told Lester that he had put the gun someplace where no one would find it.<p>

He also testified that he had known for several months that Joyner and Jones were having an affair.<p>

On cross- examination, Sadow tried to show that Lester's memory might not be accurate because of the large amount of alcohol he consumed on the night he spoke with Joyner in Newark, and because Lester made assumptions about things that Joyner didn't actually say. For example, Lester said he remembered Joyner saying he had accidentally shot his wife. But she was not shot. Lester also said Joyner was scratched up and had cuts on his hands when he saw him in Newark.<p>


<b>August 23</b><br>
The day's testimony focused on shell casings found at the crime scene.<p>


A report, prepared by prosecution witness <b>Bernadette Davy</b>, concluded that the casings found at the Camp Creek Parkway probably came from a Bryco or Lorcin semi-automatic handgun. However, Davy also testified at length about which casings were probably fired from the same weapon, which appeared to have been exposed to the elements longer than the others, which were made by the same manufacturers.<p>

She also testified at length that these brands of guns often jam, and demonstrated ways that this could happen. This is important because it could provide prosecutors with a reason for why Joyner didn't just shoot his wife, too, after he shot Halima Jones.<p>

The defense asked that Davy's testimony be stricken from the record because she testified to much more than was indicated in her report. This, the defense contended, was a violation of discovery rules. Defense attorney Steven Sadow said the expert should not be allowed to testify to information not included in her report.<p>

The judge initially ruled against Sadow, but then reserved ruling until hearing arguments Monday morning on the issue.<p>



<b>August 26</b><br>

The state rested its case against presenting testimony from five witnesses. The defense then started its case with testimony from defendant Lewis Joyner. <p>

As he had during his opening argument, defense attorney Steven Sadow had Joyner approach the jury. This time, the defense lawyer asked jurors to touch the defendant -- to examine the welt on his right finger he claims resulted from his wife biting him during the struggle that ended in her death.<p>

The prosecutor also brought the defendant off the stand, asking him on cross-examination to use a dummy to demonstrate on the floor of the courtroom the progression of his altercation with his wife.<p>

At the beginning of today's session, after hearing additional argument, the judge denied a defense motion to strike the testimony of Bernadette Davy.<p>

<b>Samuel House</b>, a Georgia Bureau of Investigation crime scene specialist, testified that he examined the van and the bodies at the airport. House said that the absence of blood spatter, hair wads and a bullet inside the van indicated that both victims were killed someplace else. He said debris on Halima Jones legs suggested that she, like Ruby Joyner was killed in a wooded or overgrown area. He maintained the debris on Jones could not have been transferred from Joyner.<p>

Toxicologist <b>Joanne Cox</b> testified that cocaine was found in Halima Jones body. She said Jones probably took the drug within 30 minutes of her death.<p>

<b>Frank Kendall</b>, a fingerprint identification specialist, testified that only two of the latents lifted in this case were suitable for comparison and both were negative in comparison to Jeff Lester and Lewis Joyner.<p>

<b>Anthony Garitta</b>, a patrol officer for the New York City Housing Police testified about Joyner's arrest on the Harlem roof top. He said he observed Joyner drinking on the roof of a 21-story building in Harlem and that the defendant ''went nuts'' when he tried to place him under arrest. With the assistance of a number of other officers, he handcuffed Joyner, who was in possession of a small bottle of cocaine powder. The defendant and several officers received minor injuries in the scuffle. The witness said Joyner has lost a great deal of weight since his arrest.<p>

The defense case started after the judge rejected a motion for a directed verdict of acquittal.

<b>Lewis Joyner</b> began his testimony denying that he killed Halima Jones, and admitting he killed his wife in self-defense. He testified he became involved with Jones in late 1994, after he had been married to his wife, Ruby, for about 18 years. During his affair with Jones, he and she used cocaine regularly.<p>

Joyner said he was confronted by John Dunbar in March of 1995 and by his wife in June of 1995 about the affair, but he denied it to both.<p>

In September of 1995, Jones decided to move out of Dunbar's apartment and Joyner helped her falsify an application to get a rent-subsidized apartment. She continued to live with Dunbar, however, until late October. Joyner had a key to the apartment. which he kept in his Jimmy.<p>

On October 20, Joyner said he and his wife had several friends over, including Jones. After Jones left, he said, he told his wife that he needed to run and errand and met Jones at her apartment. He got home about 1:30 am, but claimed there was no problems with his wife.<p>

The next day, Saturday, the Joyners went to Florida for a vacation. They planned to stay for several days. But on Sunday, Joyner said he called Dunbar's house and learned Jones abruptly moved out. Joyner said he decided that he needed to go back to Atlanta to find out what was going on so he made an excuse to his wife and flew home.<p>

The next day, Monday, October 23, Joyner claimed his wife was mugged in the hotel room. Her eyes, ankles and legs were bruised, he said. Joyner flew back to Florida that night to be with his wife. The assault was not reported to the hotel or to the police.<p>

After the incident, Ruby Joyner became very fearful,  Joyner said, and asked him to get her a gun. The defendant testified he refused.<p>

On November 15, Joyner testified he met his wife and Jones at a bar near the airport. When the women arrived in Jones' van, Ruby Joyner went inside. Jones was in the driver's seat and Joyner got into the passenger seat. Jones and Lewis Joyner were kissing, when Ruby Joyner came back to the van and knocked on the driver's window.<p>

According to the defendant, his wife suggested the three go to a bar she knew and got into the driver's seat. Jones was sitting on the floor in the back of the van, and she and Joyner began to do cocaine.<p>

After about 15 minutes of driving around, apparently lost, Joyner said his wife pulled over and got out of the van. He said he heard her say ''You cheating, bitch,'' looked up and saw her standing by the open driver's door, pointing a gun at Jones.<p>

Joyner said he heard a shot and jumped out the driver's door, past his wife, possibly knocking her into the side of the van. As he ran he heard at least two more shots.<p>

Joyner said he ran into a wooded area where he tripped and fell face forward. His wife then jumped on him and they struggled. He said he saw the gun pointed at him as he rolled over onto his back still under his wife, and thought he was going to die.<p>

The defendant said he managed to get on top of his wife, but she got the fingers of his right hand into her mouth. The gun was in her right hand and she was hitting and scratching him with her left hand. Joyner said he got his left hand on the gun, which was still in his wife's right hand, and began hitting her about the head. Eventually, he said, he pressed either the gun or his left hand into his wife's throat and she released his right hand.<p>

Thinking his wife was unconscious, Joyner claimed he went back to the van where he found Jones dead. He then went back into the woods and discovered his wife also was dead.<p>

Joyner said he then dragged his wife's body out of the woods and put her in the van. After driving around for a while, Joyner said he covered the bodies with a comforter that was in the back of the van, parked the van at the airport and took a cab back to the bar where he had left his car.<p>

Joyner said  he put the gun back into his wife's purse, which he took with him along with Jones' purse. Then he went home, showered and rested for a while before he called Dunbar to ask him about his wife's whereabouts. Joyner said he called Dunbar to alert him that there were children unattended at Jones' apartment.<p>

Joyner conceded he tried to go back to the crime scene to find his sunglasses, pager, license and cap, but got scared off when he saw an officer running his license plate. Joyner went to buy a new pager, then checked into a Days Inn. He admitted he disposed of the women's purses and his bloody clothes in a dumpster.<p>

The next morning, Joyner flew to New York, where he replaced his driver's license and checked into a hotel. He spoke to police on the telephone and contacted his sister. The defendant claimed he planned to return to Georgia in a few days.<p>

Instead, Joyner said he discovered the police were lying to him, so he consulted a lawyer in New York who advised him not to talk to the police  and not to go home until he had retained a lawyer in Georgia.<p>

Joyner admitted he asked Lester to come to New York and discussed the incident with him. He also conceded they talked about Lester trying to go to the crime scene to retrieve Joyner's possessions. The two were drinking and Joyner said they even discussed hiring a private eye or using blood hounds to find the location.<p>

On the day of his arrest, Joyner said he was drinking and doing cocaine. He had decided to commit suicide when he went up on the roof of a building in Harlem where he was apprehended.<p>

On cross-examination, prosecutor Penny Penn focused on Joyner's lies to his wife about his affair, his lack of gainful employment and his uses of aliases. She also questioned him about the oddities in his account of the Florida trip and had him repeat his account of the killings, demonstrating the fatal struggle with his wife using a dummy on the floor of the courtroom.<p>



<b>August 27</b><br>
The trial came to an end as Lewis Joyner concluded his testimony and the defense presented two other witnesses before resting its case.<p>

The jury now must consider six charges against Joyner -- malice murder, felony murder and aggravated assault in the death of Ruby Joyner and similar charges in the death of Halima Jones.<p>


The prosecution's theory of the case is that Joyner and Jones plotted to murder Ruby Joyner but that Joyner accidentally shot and killed Jones. The state claims the defendant fired at his wife until he ran out of bullets, chased her down, then beat her with the gun and strangled her with his hands. <p>

The jury could convict of malice murder in the death of Jones, because  Georgia law defines the charge as ''deliberate intention unlawfully to take the life of another human being.'' If the jury accepts that Joyner had the intent to kill his wife when he fired the bullet that killed Jones, they can convict of malice murder for the death of Jones.<p>

The prosecution concluded its cross-examination of Joyner by presenting its theory of the case. Joyner denied that he had the gun throughout the incident or that he and Jones schemed to kill his wife. Joyner also denied that he accidentally killed Jones as he was shooting at his wife or that he ran out of bullets before he could shoot Ruby Joyner.<p>

On re-direct examination, Joyner indicated his family was not present in court because defense attorney Steven Sadow told him to ask them not to come to avoid conflict with his wife's family. He stated he was never athletic and indicated he was  afraid to go to police because of his unrelated and unspecified shady dealings.<p>

<b>Cynthia Neely</b>, a former waitress at the Peachtree City Executive Center, testified that she served Joyner with his wife and Jones several times and with only Halima on a number of other occasions. She said she believed Jones was Joyner's wife.<p>

The defense's final witness was <b>Charisse Lewis</b>. The Joyners   were friends of her parents, and she went to work for Lewis Joyner's company in 1990. She attained a position superior to Ruby Joyner's in the business and tension developed between them.<p>

On one occasion, she and Ruby Joyner argued and Ruby came after her, swinging at and striking her. Another employee grabbed Ruby, ending the confrontation. Lewis believed Ruby Joyner was professionally jealous of her and resented her youth and success.<p>

The witness did not observe Ruby Joyner behaving violently on any other occasion, but described her as holding things in . She never saw Lewis Joyner behave violently and considers him to be like a father to her.<p>

In closing arguments, defense attorney Sadow focused on the burden of proof and the requirement that to support a conviction, circumstantial evidence must exclude every reasonably hypothesis other than guilt.<p>

Sadow emphasized the distinction between a verdict of not guilty and a belief in innocence, highlighting the charge on bare suspicion--that is, that facts which simply raise suspicion, speculation or conjecture of the defendant's guilt is insufficient to convict.<p>

The defense lawyer also told the jury of the state's burden to disprove Joyner's self-defense claim beyond a reasonable doubt.<p>

Prosecutor Penny Penn emphasized Joyner's flight after his wife disappeared, his efforts to conceal evidence of his involvement in the deaths of his wife and Jones, his lies to the authorities and others in the days following the disappearance of the women, and the violence of his resistance when he was arrested in New York.<p>

The prosecutor described Ruby Joyner's Florida ''mugging'' as set-up by her husband and as a failed attempt.<p>

Penn suggested that Joyner and Jones set up the November 15, 1995, outing and that both ingested huge amounts of cocaine. She insisted that only  Joyner had the gun and that all three people were outside the van when the assault began.<p>

Penn argued that Jones was shot near the van and fell on the pavement, causing the marks noted on her face. She explained the absence of blood on the pavement as resulting from the passage of time before the scene was located.<p>

The prosecutor maintained that Jones was shot as Joyner tried to shoot his wife, and that after he had fires several rounds his gun jammed. She attributed the live round found on the pavement to Joyner's clearing the jam before he emptied the magazine firing at his wife.<p>

Penn argued Joyner caught up with his wife in the woods and using the butt of the gun like a hammer, viciously beat her. She acknowledged that Ruby Joyner probably did scratch and bite her husband ''fighting for her life.''<p>

The prosecutor argued that the number and severity of Ruby Joyner's wounds were inconsistent with Joyner's claim of self-defense. <p>


<BR CLEAR=ALL>

