<TITLE>Court TV Trial Report</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#BB0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<IMG SRC="/report/trheader.gif" ALT="Trial Report" WIDTH="600" HEIGHT="90" BORDER="0">

<H3>The State's Case</H3>

On January 10, 1995, at approximately 10:15 p.m., Lawrence, Massachusetts police officer William Beck responded to the Holy Family Hospital in Metheun after receiving information about an alleged robbery and stabbing. In the hospital emergency room, he learned that John McIntyre had carried a bleeding Meredith Coppola into the hospital moments earlier. Beck saw blood on McIntyre's hands and pants.<p>

McIntyre, 25, told police at the hospital that he and Coppola, 18, were together in his car before she was stabbed but that he was not  responsible for her death. He told police he left his car to buy some marijuana. And when he returned, he found Coppola bleeding.<p>

McIntyre told Beck that he and his girlfriend had driven together to buy some marijuana and that he had left his car in order to make a deal. McIntyre said that after a hassle over money with the alleged dealers,  he ran back to his car followed by two Spanish males who went to the passenger's side of the car. McIntyre said he got into the car, touched Coppola and noticed she was bleeding.<p>

Two detectives soon arrived at the hospital. McIntyre told the detectives the same story, this time adding that he had been robbed by the two Spanish males who chased him back to the car. He also said he could not identify the men or Coppola's assailant. <p>

Coppola died at approximately 2 am on January 11. McIntyre eventually left the hospital.<p>

When the detectives inspected McIntyre's car in the hospital parking lot, they saw a large amount of blood on the passenger side seat and door. They also observed an empty black knife sheath on the driver's side floor. The car was then impounded.<p>

During their investigation, police discovered that earlier on the night of January 10, Coppola had been visiting some friends. McIntyre showed up soon after and the two had a fight. Just before 10pm, the two left the party arguing. <p>

McIntyre was arrested on January 11.<p>

After he was arraigned, McIntyre's friend Jill Monroe turned over a knife to police. She said that in the early morning hours after the stabbing, McIntyre came to her home and told her that he was in trouble. Monroe said McIntyre washed off blood from a knife he had and left the knife at her home. An analysis of the knife revealed traces of blood and fibers consistent with the sweater Coppola was wesaring when she was stabbed. The knife also fit the sheath found in mcIntyre's car.<p>

Prosecutors also will try to introduce evidence that Coppola obtained a temporary restraining order against McIntyre in 1993. The order lapsed two weeks later when Coppola and McIntyre did not show up for a  final hearing.<p>

And in January 1994, McIntyre was arrested and charged with assault and battery against Coppola. The prosecutors in that case alleged that Coppola reluctantly testified, wanted the case dismissed and minimized the entire incident. McIntyre was acquitted and he continued his relationship with Coppola.<p>


<h3>The Defense Case</H3>

The defense contends McIntyre did not kill Coppola. The defendant is expected to stick to his story that he was shopping for drugs when Coppola was stabbed. The defense also is expected to argue that Coppola's dying declaration cleared McIntyre<p>







