<HEAD>







<TITLE>Court TV Trial Report</TITLE>







</HEAD>



<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#BB0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">







<IMG SRC="/report/trheader.gif" ALT="Trial Report" WIDTH="600" HEIGHT="90" BORDER="0">







<H3>The Key Testimony</H3>


Anthony Riggs was fatally shot in March 1991, less than two weeks after returning home from military service during Operation Desert Storm. The crime was viewed by many as a brutal irony -- Riggs, 22, had survived the war but not the streets of Detroit. The Rev. Jesse Jackson accompanied Toni Cato Riggs to her husband's funeral and his eulogy included a plea to stop the violence.<p>

A week after the funeral, Cato Riggs was arrested after her brother Michael told police that his sister hired him to kill Riggs. The motive was to collect $150,000 in life insurance. He was eventually convicted of the actual shooting and sentenced to life in prison.<p>

The charges against Cato Riggs were dismissed on technical grounds, and it would be more than two years before authorities, armed with new evidence, again would arrest her for murder.<p>

The main evidence during the trial were video and audiotapes in which Cato Riggs told undercover agents, posing as drug kingpins, of her involvement in her husband's death.<p>

After collecting the insurance money, she allegedly got involved in the drug business. In April 1992, she went to Texas with Reginald Gilbert-Rey and Rosita De La Paz to pick up 10 kilograms of cocaine, according to federal authorities. Cato Riggs decided to return home early to take a college exam but her partners were arrested.<p>

De La Paz told Drug Enforcement Administration agents about Cato Riggs, and agents in Detroit subsequently were tipped off about her desire to continue in the drug business despite the close call in Texas. After she unwittingly contacted an informant, DEA agents set up a meeting in a Detroit-area apartment on February 23, 1993.<p>

The agents, posing as leaders of a high level narcotics ring, told Cato Riggs that if she wanted to work for them as a drug courier she had to be honest about everything. It was then that she began to tell them about her husband's death.<p>

During the meeting, Cato Riggs said that when she and her brother went to Ft. Bliss in Texas to meet her husband upon his return from the Persian Gulf, Michael Cato said, "if we do this there's no turning back."<p>

"I know," Cato Riggs responded.<p>

Prosecutors claimed she lured her husband back to Detroit when he didn't want to come. The couple had a history of marital problems and he was planning to grant her a divorce. Cato Riggs told the agents she knew her brother was waiting outside their grandmother's house on the night Anthony Riggs was killed.<p>

During a second meeting on March 28, 1993, Cato Riggs allegedly put out a $10,000 contract for the murder of one of the witnesses in the case. She told DEA agent Richard Crock that she wanted Antonio Shelby "eliminated period. No coming back, no nothing."<p>

The prosecution believed she wanted Shelby dead because he was a potential witness against her. He testified that he lent his gun to Michael Cato several hours before Riggs was shot.<p>

During the trial, defense attorney Anthina Siringas tried to show Cato Riggs was bullied into making the incriminating admissions in order to impress the agents she thought were tough drug dealers. Agent Crock admitted that even though he was running a narcotics operation, he planned to ask Cato Riggs about the murder. She brought up the fatal shooting before he could put his plan into action, he said.<p>

The defense attorneys previously argued the statements were not admissible because Cato Riggs was not read her Miranda rights. But the judge ruled the tapes could be played for the jury because it was part of a separate undercover investigation in which Cato Riggs' rights to have a lawyer present did not apply.<p>


<BR CLEAR=ALL>



