HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 08:54:50 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 25-Jul-96 01:39:01 GMT
Content-length: 15610
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Court TV Trial Report</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#BB0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<IMG SRC="/report/trheader.gif" ALT="Trial Report" WIDTH="600" HEIGHT="90" BORDER="0">

<H3>The Key Testimony</H3>
<b>July 19</b><br>
Several witnesses testified the defendants' fingerprints were not found at the crime scene. But Blades's prints were found in the victim's car.<p>

Memphis police officer <b>Phil Nason</b> said he processed the Fisher house on the day of the murder and did not find any prints. He said he went back the next day and found some partial prints on the banister, a picture frame and a table.<P>

<b>Paulette Sutton</b>, a serologist, said she went to the Fisher house on the day of the murder and found blood everywhere. She said the different blood patterns on the walls, ceilings and floors showed a tremendous struggle had taken place. She said patterns from the victim's bloody hair on the wall indicated she was dragged from room to room; blood spatters on the ceiling showed a bloody knife was being wielded through the air; and a gap in a blood trail showed she was trying to stop the bleeding as she moved through the house. The struggle took place in several rooms. Blood was in the master bedroom on the second floor, on the staircase, in most of the rooms on the first floor.<p>

Sutton said she removed blood samples and sent them to an FBI lab. She did not give the results of the tests. But neither of the defendants' blood was found at the house and one drop of blood matching no one was found.<p>

<b>Bruce Holbrook</b> said he dusted the Fisher's station wagon and found several fingerprints inside and outside the car and on a Palmolive bottle inside the vehicle.<p>

And finally, Andre Nagoski said the prints found in the station wagon matched Blades. He said none of the prints matched Tate. He also said partial prints found at the Fisher home did not match the defendants or any of the Fishers.<p>

<b>July 20</b><br>
Jurors heard from the victim's family, a jail house informant and about the connection between one of the defendants and the victim's son.<p>

<b>Thomas Zimmer</b>, a National Insurance Crime Bureau special agent, testified that Fisher's car was not hot-wired. He said someone unsuccessfully tried to hot-wire and "jimmy" it. Zimmer noted that the only way the car could have been stolen was with the keys -- suggesting the car thief took the keys after killing Fisher. The car was found near the home of the defendants.<p>

The next witness, <b>Al Bond</b>, a neighbor of Blades, said he saw the defendant on the day of the murder walking away from the area where Fisher's car was found. Bond said Blades was carrying a bag similar to Fisher's. Bond said he saw Blades again later that night and that Blades told him he had come up with some money.<p>

Although Bond was a key witness for police early in the investigation, he wasn't very cooperative with prosecutors in court. He originally told police Blades told time he got $150 from a bag that was in a green Taurus. But on the witness stand, Bond said he could not remember where Blades said he got the money or how much he got. Prosecutor Jerry Harris had to cross-examine his own witness by showing his earlier statement and pointing out inconsistencies with his testimony.<p>

On cross-examination, Blades's attorney pointed out that several people walked past Fisher's car that day. Bond said his brother even got arrested for looking in the car. The defense admits Blades was in the car but only after it was abandoned near his house.<p>

Tate's lawyer asked Bond whether he saw Blades with Tate that day. Bond said no, adding Blades and Tate rarely were seen together.<p>

<b>Andrew Johnson</b> was even more uncooperative with prosecutors. He said his earlier statement to police was bogus because he was high on drugs. But the statement was allowed into evidence and was potentially devastating to Blades.<p>

In March of 1995, Johnson told police he saw Blades driving Fisher's station wagon on the night of the murder. In his statement, Johnson said Blades came to his house later that night. He was shaking and nervous and asked for $50. He said his sister's house caught on fire. And he left with another black male in a dark green station wagon.<p>

But on the witness stand, Johnson said he never saw Blades get in the station wagon. He said he had been smoking and shooting dope for four days straight when police questioned him. He said the police mentioned something about cutting down his jail time on another charge and then shoved a picture of the station wagon in his face. Prosecutor Harris pointed out that Johnson signed his name on the back of the picture and wrote, "this is the car I saw Rodney in."<p>

<b>Keith Summerville</b> then offered incriminating testimony against Blades. In the summer of 1995, Summerville was in jail for violating probation and selling drugs. In the holding tank, while waiting to be booked, he met Blades. Summerville said Blades confessed to the murder but wasn't worried because all police had on him was his fingerprints in Fisher's car. <p>

According to Summerville, Blades described the killing: he said they went in through a side door and "one tied the black lady and one was down the stairs with the white lady." He said he slapped her around and asked where the money was and then stabbed her.<p>

Summerville got absolutely nothing in return for his statement. He served his entire sentence. When asked why he ratted on Baldes, Summerville, who lives with his grandmother, said "that could have been my grandparents."<p>

<b>Hubert Fisher</b> cried on the witness stand as he described his wife of 25 years and the mother of his two children. It was through his testimony that jurors learned of the link between the couple's son, Adrian, and Tate. Fisher told the jury that Adrian, 21, had been stealing money from him to support a $250-a-day cocaine habit. He said Adrian went into the family safe and took $9,000 in savings bonds, a $7,0000 Rolex watch and a $1,000 gold chain.<p>

Fisher said he began suspecting his son was taking the money and that he  had a drug problem when he found a bag of white powder in his bedroom. Meanwhile, Adrian began hanging around kids from Klondyke, a run-down drug-ridden neighborhood in north Memphis. One of them was Tate. He once saw Adrian and Tate in his house, where Adrian was arguing with his mother to give him some money. Fisher said he saw Tate three other times in Tate's neighborhood.<p>

<b>Adrian Fisher</b> confirmed for jurors that during the year before his mother's death, he was a hopeless cocaine addict, who cruised the north Memphis drug hangouts and stole thousands of dollars from his parents.<p>

Fisher said he tried to hide his wealth when he hung out in the Klondyke section of Memphis "because that would make me look like a spoiled brat, which I am." He said, "I wasn't trying to let anyone know because that would put my mother's life in jeopardy."<p>

But he cruised around in a red Ford Bronco and told at least two friends about his parents' safe in the upstairs closet. He admitted that he started a friendship with Tate. But he could not remember whether he told Tate about the safe. The two were arrested in 1994 for possession of marijuana.<p>

The witness eventually completed a rehabilitation program and moved to a halfway house in Minneapolis to continue his treatment. He did not go back to Memphis until his mother died. <p>

On cross-examination, Tate's attorney Glenn Wright pointed out that Adrian Fisher had several black friends who came with him to his house. He got the witness to admit that he told people other than Tate about the family safe. Wright asked Adrian to describe several kids from the neighborhood who he knew or had befriended. Some of them were short and young -- 15 or 16-years-old. This is important because one witness described two short, black kids of that age at the Fisher house on the day of the murder. Besides, there was blood found at the murder scene which did not belong to the victims or the defendants. Tate's attorneys contend the state has the wrong man -- just because Tate was friends with Adrian does not make him a  murderer.<P>

<b>July 22</b><br>
The jury saw Leester Redmond, the maid who survived the attack, identify Blades and Tate as the men who fatally stabbed Fisher. But the defense scored some points when a DNA expert testified that several samples taken from the crime scene did not match either victim or the defendants.<p>

<b>Dennis Benjamin</b>, a Memphis police officer, testified that on March 1, 1995, he went to an abandoned house where Blades was staying. He handcuffed Blades and searched the house. He found two sports jackets belonging to Fisher's husband, a bag that belonged to Fisher and the owner's manual to her car in a trash can.<p>

Benjamin also said he later interviewed Keith Summerville, who told the police officer that Blades confessed to him at the jail. Benjamin said Summerville was not the typical jail house informant. He said Summerville did not ask for or receive anything in exchange for his information. Summerville previously testified that he went to authorities because he felt sorry for the victims.<p.

It was through the testimony of Sheriff's Deputy <b>Ronald Goodwin</b>
that the videotaped deposition of Redmond was introduced into evidence. On the tape, Redmond identified Blades and Tate. She said they knocked on the door, came inside, argued with Fisher and then slugged her. Redmond said she reached for the phone but the assailants grabbed her arm and demanded to know where the family safe was kept. She said she grabbed another phone but one attacker tried to tie her up with it and then dragged her down the stairs. But Redmond escaped and ran out the door. She went  to a neighbor's house to call for help.<p>

Defense attorneys were able to cross-examine Redmond during the deposition. But Tate had different lawyers back then, so his current attorneys did not and will not have a chance to question Redmond.<p>

On cross-examination, Blades's attorney established that Redmond could not even remember her own age. The defense theory is that Redmond is too old and senile to be a credible witness.<p>

Redmond has changed her story several times. She sometimes said there were two attackers; she sometimes said there were three. During the deposition, she said police showed her only two pictures -- those of Tate and Blades. But several police officers insisted they showed her six different pictures. In the deposition, she said she was just getting home when the attackers came to the house. But in police statements, she said she was doing the dishes.<p>

<b>Police officer E.R. McCommon</b>testified that he showed Redmond six photographs, from which she picked out Tate and Blades.<p>

Redmond's niece <b>Janeth McChristian</b> was present at the deposition. She said police were very fair when they talked to her aunt and did not tell her who to pick out in the photos. But the defense again showed that Redmond does not know how old she is. Redmond said she was 74, but McChristian said Redmond is actually 94 years old.<p>

<b>Dr. Harold Deadman</b>, a DNA expert formerly with the FBI, said he did DNA tests on blood samples taken from the crime scene. None of them matched the defendants. In fact, three samples belonged to someone other than the defendants or the victims. "Someone is bleeding in that house other than these four individuals," he said.<p>

<b>July 23</b><br>
Prosecutors rested their case after calling the medical examiner, <b>Gerry Francisco</b>. He testified that Emily Fisher was stabbed so many times he lost count after 50. 

<p><b>The Defense Case</B><br>
Both defendants chose not to testify. Tate did not call any witnesses. Blades presented several witnesses to explain why his fingerprints were found in Emily Fisher's car.</P>

<p><b>Haywood Walter, Grace Montgomery</b> and <b>Sandra Leverson</b> live in the Klondyke area where Fisher's car was found. They all said it was not unusual to find abandoned cars parked on the street. The defense theory is that kids in the neighborhood stole Fisher's car and that Blades merely found it abandoned in the street.</P>

<p>Leverson said she saw the car parked on the street from February 28 to March 1. Her testimony contradicts a prosecution witness who testified that he saw Blades driving the car on the night of February 28.</P>

<p><b>Gaylor King</b> and <b>John Williams</b> testified that they were with Blades February 28. They said Blades' sister's home burned down and they drove around in a white chevette. This testimony helped support Blades' claim that he was not driving Fisher's station wagon that night.</P>

<P>The defense's final witness <b>Dr. John Huttson</b>, a clinical psychologist, testified that Redmond was not competent to testify as a witness. Huttson was originally hired by the prosecution to determine Redmond's competence. But the defense capitalized on his opinion that the woman suffers from severely impaired short term memory. Hutton said Redmond could not remember her age and what time of the year the attack took place and other basic facts. He also said she had a tendency to latch onto ideas -- accurate or not -- and stick to them even when confronted with logical inconsistencies.</P>

<p><b>Closing Arguments</b><br>
Both sides were extremely impassioned. Prosecutor Jerry Harris got choked up as he talked about the horror of what happened to Fisher. Tate's attorney Glenn Wright bellowed that Tate and Blades are victims of a rush to judgment by the state. Blades attorney Loyce Lambert vehemently insisted that the state was trying to take the easy way out by charging her client with murder.</P>

<P>Prosecutors argued that they met their burden of proof by introducing Blades' fingerprints in Fisher's car, a jail house informer who said Blades admitted to the murder, and Redmond's taped deposition.</P>

<P>But Lambert argued it was too much of a stretch to conclude that Blades is a killer just because his prints were found in Fisher's car. As for the jail house informer, Lambert dismissed him as a common criminal looking for a deal. She told jurors to disregard Redmond's videotaped deposition, saying she was senile, confused and  couldn't even remember her own age. She said Blades is a "rogue" and a "petty thief," but not a murderer.</P>

<P>Wright accused prosecutors of charging Tate with the murder and then looked for ways to make their allegations stick. </P>

<P>Wright reminded jurors he was not there to defend Blades, pointing out that no evidence connects Blades to Tate. No one saw them that day, and no fingerprints of Tate were found in Fisher's car.</P>

<p>In the state's rebuttal, Harris asked jurors not to dismiss Redmond's deposition because of her age, reminding them that she, too,  is a victim. He went to great length to explain away the blood found in the house, which matches neither the victims or the defendants.</P>

<p>He ended by suggesting that Tate repeatedly stabbed Fisher in the head to assure she died. Harris argued that the one who did that was thinking, "she's not dead and she knows me."</P>

<p><b>July 24</b><br>
In the first day of deliberations, the jury acquitted George Tate and Rodney Blades on all charges.





<BR CLEAR=ALL>
