<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<h2>Associate Justice Sandra Day O'Connor</h2>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15 SRC="/graphics/ctv/supreme/oconnor.gif">
<B>Personal Data</B><BR>
Born:  March 26, 1930 in El Paso, Texas<BR>
Married:  John Jay O'Connor III, 1952<BR>
Children:  Scott, Brian, and Jay<BR>
<p>
<B>Education</B><BR>
Stanford University, BA,1950<BR>
Stanford University, LLB,1952<BR>
<p>
<B>Legal Positions</B><BR>
Deputy County Attorney San Mateo County, CA, 1952-1953.<BR>
Civilian Attorney for Quartermaster Market Center, Frankfurt, Germany 1954-1957.<BR>
Private practice of law in Maryvale, Arizona 1958-1960.<BR>
Assistant Attorney General for  State of Arizona 1965-1968.<BR>
<p>
<B>Legislative Offices</B><BR>
Appointed State Senator in 1969, reelected twice, serving  from 1969 to 1975.<BR>
Elected Arizona Senate Majority Leader in 1972; served as Chairwoman of the State, County, and Municipal Affairs Committee in 1972 and 1973.<BR>
Served on the Legislative Council, on the Probate Code Commission, and on the Arizona Advisory Council on Intergovernmental Relations.<BR>
<p>
<B>Judicial Offices</B><BR>
Elected judge of the Maricopa County Superior Court, Phoenix, Arizona. Served from 1975-1979.<BR>
Appointed to the Arizona Court of Appeals by Governor Bruce Babbitt, serving from 1979-1981.<BR>
Nominated Associate Justice of the  Supreme Court of the United States by President Ronald Reagan on July 7, 1981. Sworn in September 25, 1981.<BR>
<p>
<B>Civic Activities</B><BR>
Member, National Board of the Smithsonian Associates, 1981-present.<BR>
President, Member, Board of Trustees of the Heard Museum, 1968-1974.<BR>
Member, Salvation Army Advisory Board, 1975-1981<BR>
Member of the Board of Trustees of Stanford University, 1976-1981.<BR>
