<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>Trying to quash a government subpoena for records relating to the launch of its online service, Microsoft Corp. filed this petition June 23, 1995 in federal court in New York.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK

________________________________________X
                                        :
MICROSOFT CORPORATION,                  :
          Petitioner,                   :
                                        :
     -against-                          :
                                        :
ANNE K. BINGAMAN, in her                :
official capacity as Assistant Attorney :
General in charge of the Antitrust      :
Division of the United States           :
Department of Justice,                  :
          Respondent.                   :
                                        :
________________________________________X

    Misc. Action No. 94-

VERIFIED PETITION OF MICROSOFT
CORPORATION FOR AN ORDER SETTING ASIDE
CIVIL INVESTIGATIVE DEMAND NO. 13187

 Petitioner Microsoft Corporation ("Microsoft"), by its
undersigned attorneys, respectfully states as follows:

  1. Microsoft is a corporation organized and existing under
the laws of the State of Washington, with its principal place of
business at One Microsoft Way, Redmond, Washington 98052-6399.

  2. Microsoft was founded in 1975. The company develops and
markets licences a wide range of software productsproducts used
in computers. Microsoft provides operating system software
products, such as MS-DOS, Windows, Windows NT and (soon) Windows
95. Microsoft provides applications software -- including Word
and Excel, Microsoft's popular word processing and spreadsheet
software products -- for both IBM-compatible computers and the
Apple Macintosh. Microsoft provides a variety of software
development tools and programming languages that can be used by
independent software developers ("ISVs") to create applications
software products that will run on Microsoft operating systems.
Microsoft manufactures hardware peripherals like the mouse
pointing device.

  3. Respondent is the Assistant Attorney General in charge of
the Antitrust Division of the United States Department of
Justice. Respondent signed the Civil Investigative Demand
("CID") that is the subject of this petition.

  4. Jurisdiction for the Court to hear this petition is
conferred by Section 5(e) of the Antitrust Civil Process Act, 15
U.S.C. Section 1314(e).

  5. Venue is proper in this Court under Section 5(b)(1)(B) of
the Antitrust Civil Process Act, 15 U.S.C. Section
1314(b)(1)(A), because Microsoft transacts business in the
Southern District of New York.

 CIVIL INVESTIGATIVE DEMAND NO. 13187

  6. On June 5, 1995, the Antitrust Division of the U.S.
Department of Justice (the "DOJ") served Microsoft with Civil
Investigative Demand No. 13025, dated June 4, 1995, directing
Microsoft to answer 12 interrogatories and to produce documents
responsive to 16 document production requests by 10:00 A.M. on
June 9, 1995. (A copy of the June 4 CID is annexed hereto as
Exhibit A and is made a part hereof.) The focus of the June 4
CID was The Microsoft Network ("MSN"), a new online information
service that Microsoft is planning to launch on August 24, 1995.
Microsoft has invested large sums of money in developing MSN
over the last several years in order to compete with existing
online information services like America Online, CompuServe and
Prodigy.

  7. Following negotiations between Microsoft and the DOJ, it
was agreed that Microsoft would answer all but two of the
interrogatories in the June 4 CID (as modified) by Monday, June
12, 1995, and that Microsoft would answer the remaining two
interrogatories by Wednesday, June 14, 1995. Microsoft has fully
complied with that undertaking. In addition, Microsoft and the
DOJ agreed that Microsoft would provide documents responsive to
the document production requests in the June 4 CID by Monday,
June 23, 1995. Microsoft has every expectation of meeting that
deadline as well.

  8. On June 19, 1995, respondent sent a letter informing
Microsoft that it would be receiving a "follow-up and
supplemental CID" later in the day. (A copy of that letter is
annexed hereto as Exhibit B and is made a part hereof.) In fact,
no CID was served on June 19, 1995. Instead, late Monday
evening, the DOJ sent Microsoft's counsel -- who were in
Washington, D.C. to attend a meeting with respondent on Tuesday,
June 20, 1995 -- a schedule of interrogatories and document
production requests that was not accompanied by any CID. (A copy
of that schedule is annexed hereto as Exhibit C and made a part
hereof.)

  9. Microsoft's counsel spent most of the next day in a
meeting with respondent and her colleagues, traveling back to
Seattle and New York on Tuesday evening. It was not until
Wednesday afternoon, June 22, 1995, that the DOJ faxed Civil
Investigative Demand No. 13187, dated June 21, 1995, to
Microsoft. (A copy of the June 21 CID is annexed hereto as
Exhibit D and made a part hereof.) The June 21 CID directs
Microsoft to answer 29 interrogatories (many of which contain
multiple questions) and to produce documents responsive to 16
broad document production requests by 10:00 A.M. today, June 23,
1995.

  10. On Thursday, June 22, 1995, Microsoft's counsel spoke
with the DOJ lawyer designated by respondent in an effort to
reach some accommodation concerning the June 21 CID. That
discussion was expressly without prejudice to Microsoft's rights
to challenge the June 21 CID as legally defective. The DOJ
lawyer, who had no involvement in drafting the June 21 CID and
no authority to agree to any modification of it, was unable to
explain the relevance of the information sought in the CID to
the investigation described on the face of the CID. At
approximately _:__ P.M. yesterday, the DOJ lawyer stated that
Microsoft's proposed accommodation was unacceptable to
respondent and Microsoft concluded that further negotiations
were unlikely to be productive given its need to seek relief
from the June 21 CID before 10:00 A.M. this morning.

  11. The return date specified in the June 21 CID is less than
48 hours after Microsoft first received a copy of the CID by
facsimile and less than 24 hours after Microsoft was formally
served with a copy of the CID. Given the scope information
sought in the June 21 CID and the fact that Microsoft is still
in the process of responding to an earlier CID that addresses
the same topics, the schedule set by the DOJ is obviously
unreasonable. By this petition, Microsoft respectfully asks that
the June 21 CID be set aside.

  PRELIMINARY STATEMENT

  12. Microsoft does not lightly invoke the jurisdiction of
this Court, understanding fully the reluctance of judges to
interfere with the decisions of federal enforcement agencies
concerning the appropriate scope of discovery in an
investigation. But Microsoft (and its customers and business
partners) has been subjected to a series of burdensome document
demands from the DOJ over the last two years that shows no sign
of abating.

  13. At present, Microsoft is working at a furious pace to
insure that its new operating system software, Windows 95, will
be commercially released on August 24, 1995 as currently
planned. In addition, Microsoft is putting the finishing touches
on its new entry into the online services business, MSN. Rather
than applauding Microsoft for providing consumers with
innovative new software products at low prices and for making de
novo entry in a related businesses like online information
services, the DOJ seems to be doing its level best to hinder
Microsoft's efforts.

  14. The source of the DOJ's concern is Microsoft's decision
-- which was publicly announced in November 1994, i.e., more
than more than six months ago -- to include access software for
MSN as a feature of Windows 95. There is nothing anticompetitive
about that decision, which will provide consumers with an easy
mechanism for subscribing to Microsoft's new online information
service if they choose to do so. The mere fact that MSN access
software will be available in Windows 95 does not mean that
consumers must subscribe to MSN or even that they are likely to
do so. And the inclusion of MSN access software does nothing to
impair the ability of existing online information services to
continue distributing their access to consumers as they have in
the past. In short, there is no occasion for panic.

  15. The sense of urgency surrounding the DOJ's most recent
investigation of Microsoft is all the more puzzling given the
weakness of the DOJ's legal position. To succeed with a claim
under Section 2 of the Sherman Act, 15 U.S.C. Section 2 -- the
only statute referred to in the June 21 CID -- the DOJ must
prove (i) that Windows 95 -- an operating system that has not
yet been commercially released -- provides Microsoft with the
ability to wield monopoly power or (ii) that including MSN
access software with Windows 95 will permit Microsoft to
monopolize the online information services (or come dangerously
close to doing so). Such claims are, quite frankly, ridiculous.

  16. By this simple logic, Windows 95 cannot give Microsoft
the ability to fix prices for operating system software or to
exclude competitors from the that segment of the software
business because Microsoft has yet to sell a single copy of
Windows 95. And in arguing that Microsoft might achieve some
competitive advantage by including MSN access software with
Windows 95, the DOJ ignores that such unilateral action -- even
by a monopolist -- cannot be challenged under the antitrust laws
unless it constitutes monopolization or attempted
monopolization. When America Online, CompuServe and Prodigy have
millions of subscribers and Microsoft has zero, it is spurious
for he DOJ to assert that Microsoft has a monopoly in online
information services or that there is any dangerous probability
of Microsoft achieving such a monopoly.

  17. The DOJ's insistence that Microsoft put all other
business aside at a busy and important time in order to provide
the DOJ with instant gratification of its seemingly insatiable
appetite for information from Microsoft is neither fair nor
appropriate. The June 21 CID should be set aside.

  FACTUAL BACKGROUND

  A. The FTC Investigation

  18. Microsoft is well acquainted with burdensome government
demands for information. During the investigation of the company
by the Federal Trade Commission (the "FTC") -- which began in
June 1990 and dragged on for more than three years before being
closed in August 1993 with no enforcement action having been
taken -- Microsoft complied with four subpoenas seeking
information about virtually every aspect of the company's
business. Microsoft also responded to a seemingly endless stream
of informal requests from the FTC Staff for documents and
information.

 B. The First DOJ Investigation

  19. In August 1993, the DOJ took the highly unusual step of
instituting its own investigation of Microsoft on the heels of
the FTC's three-year probe. The DOJ obtained the FTC's
investigational files which contained a mass of information
gathered from Microsoft and third parties, totaling more than
400,000 pages of documentary evidence and approximately 500
diskettes of electronically-stored information.

  20. Building on work done by the FTC Staff, the DOJ sought
further information from Microsoft and the original equipment
manufacturers ("OEMs") who license Microsoft's operating system
software for shipment with some or all of their computers. In
October 1993, the DOJ issued a CID to Microsoft seeking further
information about Microsoft's license agreements with OEMs, as
well as information regarding Microsoft's total sales of various
kinds of software products.

  21. In February 1994, after seven months of investigation,
the DOJ issued an omnibus CID seeking evidence to support
theories of antitrust liability that had been pursued without
positive result since June 1990. That CID resuscitated theories
that even the FTC Staff had considered and specifically
rejected.

  22. Following Microsoft's production of hundreds of thousands
of documents in response to the February 14 CID, the DOJ
announced that it would take the depositions of Microsoft's most
senior executives, including William H. Gates III, Microsoft's
chairman and chief executive officer. Those depositions covered
a wide range of topics.

  23. On June 17, 1994, the DOJ initiated discussions with
Microsoft concerning a possible settlement. Following four weeks
of intensive negotiations, the parties reached an agreement that
brought an end to the DOJ investigation. That agreement was
embodied in a proposed Final Judgment subject to review under
the Antitrust Procedures and Penalties Act, 15 U.S.C. Section
16(b)-(h), commonly known as the Tunney Act. The district court
declined to approve the proposed Final Judgment. See United
States v. Microsoft Corp., 159 F.R.D. 318 (D.D.C. 1995). One
week ago, however, that decision was reversed and remanded with
instructions that the Final Judgment be entered and that the
case be reassigned to another district judge for purposes of
supervising compliance with the Final Judgment. See United
States v. Microsoft Corp., 1995 WL 357850 (D.C. Cir. June 16,
1995).

  C. The DOJ's Investigation of the Intuit Merger

  24. On October 13, 1994, while the Tunney Act proceeding was
still pending, Microsoft agreed to acquire Intuit, a company
whose three major products are Quicken personal finance
software, TurboTax tax preparation software and QuickBooks
business accounting software. Microsoft develops and markets
Money, a personal finance software product that competes with
Quicken.

  25. To eliminate concern that its acquisition of Intuit might
substantially lessen competition in personal finance software --
the only line of business directly affected by the planned
transaction -- Microsoft agreed to divest its Money personal
finance software to Novell, Inc. ("Novell"), a financially
strong and technically sophisticated company with a wide range
of applications software. By adopting a "fix it first" approach,
which the DOJ encourages, Microsoft eliminated the only
overlapping product offerings of the two companies.

  26. The very same day that Microsoft filed its premerger
notification form under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act, the DOJ
served a CID on Microsoft containing. The document production
requests in the October 21 CID sought a wide range of documents
relating to the planned acquisition of Intuit and the
divestiture of Microsoft Money to Novell. Microsoft produced 44
boxes of documents responsive to the CID which, together with
Microsoft's answers to interrogatories, provided the DOJ with a
large quantities of information concerning the transaction.

  27. Despite having already gathered more than enough
information to make a decision as to whether to sue to block
Microsoft's proposed acquisition of Intuit, the DOJ issued a
wildly overbroad Second Request to Microsoft in November 1994.
Unlike the earlier October 21 CID, which focused on products
relevant to the planned transaction, the 55 interrogatories and
42 document production requests in the Second Request sought
huge quantities of information about products such as word
processing software and operating system software that Intuit
does not develop or market. Such products thus had no
conceivable relevance to whether Microsoft's proposed
acquisition of Intuit threatened to substantially lessen
competition in personal finance software. In addition, the
Second Request sought to reopen issues that had been thoroughly
explored during the DOJ's earlier investigation of Microsoft.

  28. The DOJ agreed to modify the Second Request in certain
respects to remove the most egregious requests for irrelevant
information. Even with those modifications, however, it took 60
lawyers and paralegals working seven days a week to answer the
interrogatories (those answers stand more than a foot high) and
to produce in excess of 800 boxes of documents. The overbreadth
of the Second Request delayed Microsoft's ability to declare
substantial compliance until April 7, 1995, almost six months
after the transaction was announced.

  29. On April 28, 1995, the DOJ brought an action seeking to
enjoin Microsoft's planned merger with Intuit on the strained
theory that although there would be no horizontal overlap
between the product offerings of the two companies following the
divestiture of Microsoft Money to Novell, there was a risk that
Microsoft might be able to monopolize online financial services
-- a new business in which formidable competitors like banks,
securities brokerages and insurance companies control the most
important assets, i.e., account relationships with customers.
Confronted with the prospect of months, if not years, of
additional delay, Microsoft was forced to abandon the
transaction.

  D. The DOJ's Ongoing Efforts to Regulate Microsoft's Business

  30. Apparently emboldened by Microsoft's decision to abandon
the Intuit transaction rather than suffer potentially
interminable delays, the DOJ is now seeking to intrude itself
into various other aspects of Microsoft's business. There is no
basis, however, for subjecting Microsoft to such pervasive
government regulation, nor is the DOJ authorized to serve, in
respondent's words, as a "Microsoft complaints center" for
competitors like IBM. (A copy of the May 22, 1995 New York Times
article in which that statement is quoted is annexed hereto as
Exhibit F and made a part hereof.) Such wealthy and powerful
companies are perfectly capable of fending for themselves.

  31. More importantly, the Department should not be seeking to
interfere with development of an emerging industry like on-line
information services. Such interference almost inevitably harms
consumers, which is why it has long been eschewed by antitrust
enforcement agencies in this country. The companies whose
interests the DOJ is currently championing -- America Online,
CompuServe and Prodigy -- are obviously unhappy that Microsoft
is investing heavily in the on-line information services
business, but that what competition is all about. Any attempt by
the DOJ to shield companies like America Online from the
competitive process would be antithetical to the public
interest. See generally Chattanooga Pharmaceutical Ass'n v. U.S.
Dept. of Justice, 358 F.2d 864, 867 (6th Cir. 1966)

  32. The June 21 CID is the latest salvo in what increasingly
appears to be a campaign of harassment directed against
Microsoft by the DOJ. Unfortunately, Microsoft's customers and
business partners also find themselves in the line of fire, and
their anger at being put to the trouble and expense of
responding to a seemingly endless series of demands for
information from the DOJ about their dealings with Microsoft is
becoming a serious impediment to Microsoft's ability to conduct
its business.

  33. The DOJ is vested with enormous power in investigating
potential antitrust violations which should be exercised in a
responsible manner. Microsoft's ability to protect itself from
abusive behavior by the DOJ is limited to the protections
afforded by the Antitrust Civil Process Act, 15 U.S.C. Section
1312, et seq. That statute, however, plainly prohibits the sort
of vexatious tactics reflected in the June 21 CID.

  APPLICABLE LEGAL STANDARDS

  34. The June 21 CID was served upon Microsoft in purported
compliance with the Antitrust Civil Process Act ( the "Act"), 15
U.S.C. Section 1312, et seq. Under the Act, courts are
authorized to set aside or modify a CID if the information
sought by the CID would be protected from disclosure under (i)
"the standards applicable to subpoenas or subpoenas duces tecum
issued by a court of the United States in aid of a grand jury
investigation," or (ii) "the standards applicable to discovery
requests under the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, to the
extent that the application of such standards to any such demand
is appropriate and consistent with the provisions and purposes
of this chapter." 15 U.S.C. Section 1312(c)(1).

  35. Courts interpreting 15 U.S.C. Section 1312(c)(1) have
held that a CID may be set aside or modified if it is
"unreasonable or oppressive" in violation of Rule 17(c) of the
Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure. See Associated Container
Transportation (Australia) Ltd. v. United States, 705 F.2d 53,
58 (2d Cir. 1983). A grand jury subpoena will be deemed
unreasonable or oppressive under Rule 17(c) if it is "far too
sweeping" in scope. See In re Subpoenas to Local 478,
International Union of Operating Engineers & Benefit Funds, 708
F.2d 65, 70 n.5 (2d Cir. 1983) (quoting Hale v. Henkel, 201 U.S.
43, 76 (1906)); see also United States v. Doe, 457 F.2d. 895,
899 (2d Cir. 1972), cert. denied, 410 U.S. 941 (1973).

  36. Similarly, a CID may be set aside or modified to protect
the target of a DOJ investigation from "annoyance, oppression or
undue burden or expense" if (i) the information it seeks is not
relevant to the subject matter of the investigation, Rule
26(b)(1), Fed. R. Civ. P., (ii) "the discovery sought is
unreasonably cumulative or duplicative," Rule 26(b)(2), Fed. R.
Civ. P., or (iii) the "the burden or expense of the proposed
discovery outweighs its likely benefit," id.; see H.R. Rep. No.
1343, 94th Cong., 2d Sess. 12, reprinted in [1976] U.S. Code
Cong. & Ad. News 2596, 2606.

  37. Under the terms of the Act, cases construing the Act and
the Act's legislative history, it is apparent that the June 21
CID is infirm and should be set aside.

  38. First, the Act does not permit the DOJ to conduct the
full range of discovery that would be available to it after an
enforcement action is instituted. Rather, the DOJ may use CIDs
only to seek information that is necessary to enable the DOJ "to
make a more informed judgment on whether or not to institute a
civil suit." H.R. Rep. No. 1343, 94th Cong., 2d Sess. 2,
reprinted in [1976] U.S. Code Cong. & Ad. News 2596, 2597. As
the court stated in United States v. Witmer, 835 F. Supp. 208,
219 (M.D. Pa. 1993), "using the CIDs for a purpose other than to
determine if there is sufficient evidence to file suit would be
improper."

  39. Thus, a CID may be set aside where, as here, the DOJ "is
engaged in 'an unlimited, exploratory investigation whose
purposes and limits can be determined only as it proceeds.'"
H.R. Rep. No. 1343, 94th Cong., 2d Sess. 10, reprinted in [1976]
U.S. Cong. & Ad. News 2596, 2605 (quoting In re Grand Jury
Investigation (General Motors Corp.), 174 F. Supp. 393, 395
(S.D.N.Y. 1959)). This is consistent with the general principle
that a government subpoena cannot be justified under a "claim of
'an unlimited right of access to the respondents' papers . . .
relevant or irrelevant, in hope that something will turn up.'"
Oklahoma Press Publishing Co. v. Walling, 327 U.S. 186, 207 n.40
(1946) (quoting FTC v. American Tobacco Co., 264 U.S. 298, 305
(1924)). It is impossible to determine from the face of the CID,
and has certainly never been explained to Microsoft in
comprehensible fashion by the DOJ, how the inclusion of access
software for MSN -- an online information service that has not
yet been launched -- in Windows 95 -- an operating system that
has not yet been released -- could possibly violate Section 2 of
the Sherman Act. The DOJ is not free to turn Microsoft upside
down in a quest to find something objectionable about such an
ordinary business practice.

  40. Second, the Act expressly requires the DOJ to identify,
as to each interrogatory and document request, the "conduct
constituting the alleged antitrust violations . . . which are
under investigation and the provision of law applicable
thereto." 15 U.S.C. Section 1312(b)(1)(A). The DOJ has not
complied with this requirement. Rather, the June 21 CID states
only that the DOJ is investigating whether Microsoft has engaged
in conduct that violates Section 2 of the Sherman Act, i.e.,
monopolization or attempted monopolization, by virtue of
"bundling of Microsoft Network with Windows 95." That, however,
is a complete non sequitur. MSN is an online information
service; a consumer who has chosen to license Windows 95 must
make an entirely independent decision whether to subscribe to
the network. It would be possible for Microsoft to condition the
sale of Windows 95 on a consumer's agreement to subscribe to
MSN, at which point it might make some sense to say that the
online information service had been "bundled" with the operating
system, but that would almost certainly constitute an illegal
tying arrangement under Section 1 and is, in any event, not
something Microsoft has any intention of doing. Cf. In re Union
Oil Co. of California, 225 F. Supp. 486, 487 (S.D. Cal. 1963)
(CID can be set aside as facially invalid if conduct described
as subject of investigation cannot plausibly be said to
constitute violation of antitrust statute referenced in CID),
aff'd, 343 F.2d 29 (9th Cir. 1965).

  41. Because the scope of the investigation as described on
the face of the CID is nonsensical -- MSN is an online
information service that is not, and cannot, be "bundled" into
an operating system like Windows 95 -- it is impossible for
Microsoft or this Court to assess whether particular requests
contained in the June 21 CID are proper under the Act. As the
court stated in Material Handling Institute, Inc. v. McLaren,
426 F.2d 90, 92 (3d Cir.), cert. denied, 400 U.S. 826 (1970), a
generalized statement by the DOJ that it purports to be
"investigating a possible violation of section 1 of the Sherman
Act by a 'contract or combination in unreasonable restraint of
trade'" is not sufficient to meet the requirements of the Act.
The same, of course, applies to Section 2.

  42. The test for determining whether the DOJ has complied
with its obligation to specify the conduct alleged to constitute
an antitrust violation and the law applicable to that conduct is
whether the statements in the CID are "sufficient to inform
adequately the person being investigated and sufficient to
determine the relevancy of the documents demanded for
inspection." In re Gold Bond Stamp Co., 221 F. Supp. 391, 397
(D. Minn. 1963) (emphasis in original), aff'd, 325 F.2d 1018
(8th Cir. 1964). Microsoft cannot determine how many of the
interrogatories and document production requests in the June 21
CID have any bearing on whether Microsoft's inclusion of MSN
access software as a feature of Windows 95 may violate Section
2, and the DOJ lawyer designated by respondent to discuss the
June 21 CID with Microsoft's counsel was unable to shed any
light on that subject. The DOJ's failure to articulate any
logical connection between much of the information sought in the
June 21 CID and a claim under Section 2 -- even assuming that
such a claim was legally cognizable -- is further reason to set
aside the CID.

  43. Third, the Act's requirement that the scope of the
information requested be reasonable is violated by requests for
information that relate to conduct that cannot possibly
constitute a violation of the antitrust laws. The DOJ cannot
seriously assert a monopolization or attempted monopolization
claim based on two products that have not yet been commercially
released. Even if the Court determines that the DOJ is entitled
to explore the possibility of a Section 2 claim, the glaring
flaws in the DOJ's underlying legal theory should be borne in
mind in determining whether the substantial burden imposed on
Microsoft in responding to the June 21 CID is justified,
especially on the highly expedited schedule demanded by the DOJ.

  44. Fourth, and finally, Congress specifically contemplated
that the target of a DOJ investigation could object to a CID on
that ground that it "unreasonably seeks information that has
already been provided to another Federal agency, such as the
FTC." H.R. Rep. No. 1343, 94th Cong., 2d Sess. 11, reprinted in
[1976] U.S. Code Cong. & Ad. News. 2596, 2605 (footnotes
omitted). A fortiori, a CID is objectionable if it seeks
information that has already been provided to the DOJ itself. A
substantial portion of the June 21 CID is duplicative of
requests for information contained either in the June 4 CID or
in earlier CIDs issued by the DOJ, either in connection with the
proposed Intuit merger or in the DOJ's first investigation of
Microsoft. All of those CIDs have been complied with fully by
Microsoft.

CONCLUSION

  WHEREFORE, for the reasons stated in this petition, the Court
should set aside the June 21 CID in its entirety.

 Dated: New York, New York
        June 23, 1995

     Respectfully submitted,

     ____________________________

     Richard J. Urowsky (RU0334)
     D. Stuart Meiklejohn (DM9965)
     Steven L. Holley (SH2485)
